+
+Retention metadata semantics:
+
+- `policyVersion` identifies the retention metadata contract. It is safe to
+  return through JSONL, CLI, API, and compact AI context output, and should
+  change only when the field contract or cleanup interpretation changes.
+- `policyName` names the configured cleanup policy that was active when the
+  event was written. The default Phase 6 policy is
+  `project-jsonl-30d-or-10000`, meaning a project-scoped JSONL file keeps
+  events for up to 30 days and keeps no more than the newest 10000 entries.
+- `lifecycleState` describes the current lifecycle state of the event record,
+  not the state of the user action, AI step, or gameplay event represented by
+  the record. New records are written as `active`.
+- `retentionDays` is the age-based window in whole days. A value of `0` means
+  age-based cleanup is disabled for that record; count-based cleanup can still
+  apply when `maxEntries` is greater than `0`.
+- `maxEntries` is the count cap for the project log. A value of `0` means
+  count-based cleanup is disabled for that record; age-based cleanup can still
+  apply when `retentionDays` is greater than `0`.
+- `expiresAtUtc` is the earliest UTC timestamp when age-based cleanup may mark
+  the event eligible. It is derived from the event capture timestamp plus
+  `retentionDays`; it is empty only when age-based cleanup is disabled or the
+  producer cannot compute a trusted expiry timestamp.
+- `cleanupEligible` is `true` only after a cleanup evaluator has determined
+  the event may be removed, compacted, or archived. Producers should write
+  normal new events with `cleanupEligible: false`.
+- `cleanupReason` is empty while `cleanupEligible` is `false`; when eligibility
+  is true, it contains a redacted reason such as `expired`, `entry-count-cap`,
+  `manual-policy`, `corrupt-line`, or `compacted`.
+
+Lifecycle states:
+
+| State | Meaning |
+| :--- | :--- |
+| `active` | Event is inside the configured retention window and should be returned by normal list, tail, recent, context, and API reads. |
+| `eligible` | Cleanup may remove, compact, or archive the event because at least one configured policy condition has been met. |
+| `compacted` | Event has been reduced to a smaller sanitized summary. Compacted records must still preserve schema, redaction, and retention metadata. |
+| `archived` | Event was moved out of the active project JSONL path by an explicit archive policy. Normal project reads may omit it unless an archive-aware command is used. |
+| `deleted` | Event content has been intentionally removed. This state may appear only in retained tombstones or audit summaries, not as raw deleted payload content. |
+
+Cleanup reason values:
+
+| Reason | Use |
+| :--- | :--- |
+| `expired` | `expiresAtUtc` is at or before the cleanup evaluation time. |
+| `entry-count-cap` | The event falls outside the newest `maxEntries` records for the project log. |
+| `manual-policy` | A user or tool explicitly requested cleanup under the configured retention policy. |
+| `corrupt-line` | A malformed JSONL line was quarantined, summarized, or skipped during cleanup. |
+| `compacted` | The event was replaced by a compact sanitized summary instead of being fully removed. |
+
+Reader and producer safety rules:
+
+- Retention metadata is not a substitute for redaction. The same redaction
+  policy must run before persistence, HTTP/API responses, WebSocket broadcasts,
+  and AI context generation, including for `policyName`, `lifecycleState`,
+  `expiresAtUtc`, and `cleanupReason` values read from older or external logs.
+- CLI/API/context readers must whitelist only `policyVersion`, `policyName`,
+  `lifecycleState`, `retentionDays`, `maxEntries`, `expiresAtUtc`,
+  `cleanupEligible`, and `cleanupReason` from `retentionMetadata`; unknown
+  fields are ignored rather than forwarded.
+- Project-scoped reads must not delete, compact, archive, or rewrite records.
+  Cleanup is a separate retention operation so read commands remain safe for
+  AI agents and external tooling.
+- Retention evaluators should apply both enabled policies and keep the stricter
+  result: an event is eligible if it is expired by age or falls outside the
+  count cap. Disabled policies use `0` and do not contribute eligibility.
+- Count-based cleanup is evaluated per project log after ordering records by
+  `timestampUtc` and preserving stable order for identical timestamps with the
+  JSONL line order.
+- Malformed or legacy records without retention metadata should be treated as
+  readable but retention-unknown by normal readers. Cleanup tools may attach a
+  sanitized `retentionMetadata` object during compaction or quarantine rather
+  than failing the whole project log.
+- `cleanupReason` and lifecycle values must never include raw file contents,
+  raw project paths, secret suffixes, player identifiers, save data, or
+  gameplay/private payload values.
 
